  "prompt": "What is the difference between : and ; ?",
  "response": "In most programming languages, `:` and `;` serve different purposes:\n\n`:` (Colon):\n1. Used in dictionaries/maps/associative arrays\n2. Used in type annotations\n3. Used in slicing (in Python)\n4. Used in ternary conditions\n5. Used to start code blocks in some languages (like Python)\n\nExample (Python):\n```python\n# Dictionary\nmy_dict = {'key': 'value'}\n\n# Type annotation\nx: int = 5\n\n# Slicing\nmy_list = [1, 2, 3, 4]\nslice = my_list[1:3]\n\n# Ternary condition\nresult = 'Yes' if x > 0 else 'No'\n\n# Code block\ndef my_function():\n    if x > 0:\n        print(\"Positive\")\n```\n\n`;` (Semicolon):\n1. Used to end statements in many languages\n2. Separates statements in a single line\n3. Used in for loops and some control structures\n\nExample (JavaScript/C/Java):\n```javascript\nlet x = 5;  // Statement termination\nlet y = 10; let z = 15;  // Multiple statements\n\n// In a for loop\nfor (let i = 0; i < 10; i++) {\n    // Loop body\n}\n```\n\nEach language has its specific uses, so context matters.",
